#### ***The Concept***

Vector embeddings are numerical representations of text in a multi-dimensional space that capture semantic meaning and relationships.

Words or phrases with similar meanings end up closer together in that space.

For example, if you imagine the word ‚Äúsloth‚Äù as a vector in a simple two-dimensional space, ‚Äúanteater‚Äù would be much closer to it than ‚Äúhypotenuse‚Äù, which has nothing to do with animals or living things:

![A 2D graph with two labelled points, "Sloth" and "Anteater," in a blue oval above, and "Hypotenuse" in a pink oval below. Arrows indicate x and y axes.][image3]

In a nutshell, this is how large language models encode and work with meaning beyond simple keyword matching.

You can extend this idea from single words to entire blocks of text by generating embeddings for whole headlines or summaries. Once you have those, you can compare them using **cosine similarity**:

In our sloth example, if we draw arrows from the origin to the vector coordinates, we can see that the angle between ‚Äúsloth‚Äù and ‚Äúanteater‚Äù (Œ∏1) is much smaller than the angle between ‚Äúsloth‚Äù and ‚Äúhypotenuse‚Äù (Œ∏2):

![A 2D graph with three labelled points: "Sloth" in brown, "Anteater" in blue, and "Hypotenuse" in red. Two angles, Œ∏1 and Œ∏2, are marked between vectors: Œ∏1 between "Sloth" and "Anteater" points, and Œ∏2 between "Sloth" and "Hypotenuse" points.][image4]

The dot product tells us how much two vectors point in the same direction, so when the vectors point in exactly the same direction (i.e., Œ∏ \= 0), the dot product is exactly 1\. For cosine similarity, it follows that:

* **Value closer to 1:** Vectors point in a similar direction ‚Üí similar text  
* **Value closer to 0:** Vectors are closer to being orthogonal ‚Üí less related text  
* **Value closer to \-1:** Vectors point in opposing directions ‚Üí dissimilar text

Jina AI came to the rescue again. Using the same API key as for scraping, I was able to generate vector embeddings for each article using their [embedding](https://jina.ai/embeddings/) models and store those embeddings in an additional Google Sheets column.

The plan was then simple:

#### **Why This *Could* Work (Just Not Here)**

In hindsight, vector embeddings *would* be the more robust and scalable solution **if**:

* I needed very high precision  
* I was working at a much larger scale  
* I had proper infrastructure (e.g., Python, vector databases, custom logic)

But in my case:

* I expected some level of human review  
* Data lived in spreadsheets, not databases  
* Simplicity and speed mattered more than theoretical optimality

So despite being ‚Äúclever‚Äù, this approach was a poor fit for my actual requirements (remember the Venn diagram from Part 1).

#### **Text Comparison with AI: The Solution That Worked**

After making an absolute dog‚Äôs dinner of the embeddings approach, I tried something much simpler.

I fed Gemini:

* The company name  
* The news headline  
* The summary  
* A structured prompt asking whether the new item described the same underlying news as previous entries
